    prayerPrompt: {
      prompt: 'God of the stump and the shoot, God of the axe and the song — I bring you the places in my life where the cutting has happened. The felled trees. The exposed rings. The silence where there used to be canopy. I do not ask you to undo the cutting. I ask you to show me the green. The shoot I may have missed because I was still staring at the stump. The life pushing through dead wood that I almost dismissed because it was too small to be the answer I wanted. Give me eyes for what is germinating. Give me patience for the season between the axe and the song. And when the time comes — when the shoot has grown and the water is sweet and the song is ready — give me the courage to sing it. Not a generic song. The specific song of someone who remembers the stump and marvels at what grew from it. In the name of the Root and the Branch, the Shoot and the Signal, the one in whom the sevenfold Spirit rests. Amen.',
      posture: 'Find a place where something is growing — a garden, a window box, a crack in the sidewalk where a weed has pushed through concrete. Place your hand near it without touching it. Feel the life radiating from something small and stubborn. As you pray, let the green thing beside you be your stump\'s shoot — evidence that the earth has not forgotten how to produce life, even from places that look finished. Pray with open hands, palms up, as if receiving something fragile and alive.',
    },

